{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522921","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522921"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:49:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:49:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13857"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13857"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.61,0.11,0.07,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6474"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109192"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6474","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6474"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13857"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91547"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"251"},{"type":"tags","id":"517"},{"type":"tags","id":"651"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1258"},{"type":"tags","id":"1519"},{"type":"tags","id":"1569"},{"type":"tags","id":"1957"},{"type":"tags","id":"2210"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12825"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12826"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18452"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40793"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42949"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43920"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109192"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 51-year-old man presents with a three-month history of progressive weight loss, early satiety, and recurrent vomiting after meals. He reports vomiting undigested food several hours after eating, occurring daily for the past six weeks. He has lost 10 kg over this period. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears dehydrated with a pulse rate of 100/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. On abdominal examination a succussion splash is evident. Investigations reveal haemoglobin 110 g/L (130-180). A CT scan is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENormal ranges:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EpH: 7.35-7.45\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EpCO2: 35-45 mmHg\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHCO3-: 22-28 mmol/L\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ENa+: 135-145 mmol/L\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EK+: 3.5-5.0 mmol/L\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECl-: 95-105 mmol/L\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECreatinine: 60-110 \u03bcmol/L\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following sets of biochemical and venous blood gas findings would be most consistent with this patient\u0027s recurrent vomiting?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["pH 7.30, pCO2 30 mmHg, HCO3- 14 mmol/L, Na+ 135 mmol/L, K+ 3.0 mmol/L, Cl- 110 mmol/L, Creatinine 120 \u03bcmol/L","pH 7.50, pCO2 50 mmHg, HCO3- 38 mmol/L, Na+ 138 mmol/L, K+ 3.2 mmol/L, Cl- 90 mmol/L, Creatinine 150 \u03bcmol/L","pH 7.45, pCO2 40 mmHg, HCO3- 27 mmol/L, Na+ 140 mmol/L, K+ 4.5 mmol/L, Cl- 105 mmol/L, Creatinine 80 \u03bcmol/L","pH 7.35, pCO2 45 mmHg, HCO3- 24 mmol/L, Na+ 132 mmol/L, K+ 5.5 mmol/L, Cl- 100 mmol/L, Creatinine 90 \u03bcmol/L","pH 7.25, pCO2 60 mmHg, HCO3- 26 mmol/L, Na+ 145 mmol/L, K+ 4.0 mmol/L, Cl- 108 mmol/L, Creatinine 100 \u03bcmol/L"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with gastric outlet obstruction, likely due to a distal stomach cancer. The CT scan shows a mass in the distal stomach. The most appropriate set of biochemical and venous blood gas findings for this presentation is \u003Cstrong\u003EpH 7.50, pCO2 50 mmHg, HCO3- 38 mmol/L, Na+ 138 mmol/L, K+ 3.2 mmol/L, Cl- 90 mmol/L, Creatinine 150 \u03bcmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E. These results indicate a metabolic alkalosis with respiratory compensation, hypochloraemia, hypokalaemia, and mildly elevated creatinine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn gastric outlet obstruction, persistent vomiting leads to loss of hydrochloric acid from the stomach, resulting in a contraction alkalosis. This is characterised by an elevated pH, increased bicarbonate, and low chloride levels. The pCO2 is elevated as a compensatory mechanism to the metabolic alkalosis. Hypokalaemia is common due to urinary potassium wasting in response to the alkalosis as well as hypovolaemia increased sodium retention in preference to potassium. The elevated creatinine suggests mild dehydration and pre-renal acute kidney injury from fluid losses. Not mentioned in the results, but this presentation also causes a paradoxical aciduria, as hydrogen ions are preferentially excreted over sodium (initially) and then potassium as hypokalaemia develops.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe option \u003Cstrong\u003EpH 7.30, pCO2 30 mmHg, HCO3- 14 mmol/L, Na+ 135 mmol/L, K+ 3.0 mmol/L, Cl- 110 mmol/L, Creatinine 120 \u03bcmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E represents a metabolic acidosis, which is inconsistent with gastric outlet obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EpH 7.45, pCO2 40 mmHg, HCO3- 27 mmol/L, Na+ 140 mmol/L, K+ 4.5 mmol/L, Cl- 105 mmol/L, Creatinine 80 \u03bcmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E shows normal acid-base status and electrolytes, which would be unlikely in a patient with significant vomiting and dehydration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EpH 7.35, pCO2 45 mmHg, HCO3- 24 mmol/L, Na+ 132 mmol/L, K+ 5.5 mmol/L, Cl- 100 mmol/L, Creatinine 90 \u03bcmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E indicates a normal acid-base status with mild hyponatraemia and hyperkalaemia, which is not typical for gastric outlet obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EpH 7.25, pCO2 60 mmHg, HCO3- 26 mmol/L, Na+ 145 mmol/L, K+ 4.0 mmol/L, Cl- 108 mmol/L, Creatinine 100 \u03bcmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E represents a respiratory acidosis, which would not be expected in this clinical scenario.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Gastric outlet obstruction due to distal stomach cancer can lead to metabolic alkalosis with hypochloraemia and hypokalaemia.","Vomiting associated with gastric outlet obstruction results in loss of hydrochloric acid, leading to a contraction alkalosis.","Dehydration from persistent vomiting can cause pre-renal acute kidney injury, resulting in elevated creatinine and urea."],"references":["Badi A, Naushad A, John A, Elnour K. Biochemical syndrome in adult pyloric stenosis, a clue to diagnosis in emergency deparment. Open Journal of Gastroenterology. 2014;4(12):278-382. Available online: https://www.scirp.org/journal/paperinformation?paperid=52765","Ahmad J, Thomson S, Taylor M, Scoffield J. A reminder of the classical biochemical sequelae of adult gastric outlet obstruction. BMJ Case Reports. 2011; doi: 10.1136/bcr.05.2010.2978. Available online: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3066630/#:~:text=The%20pathophysiology%20of%20the%20biochemical,and%20renal%20function%20is%20overwhelmed.      Of note; in the discussion there is a typo, mentioning metabolic acidosis, but this is against the rest of the article"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91547"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13857"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20804"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20804"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/36wgsdIRDY1FQdql2Wvcy3RD91MHX5.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/36wgsdIRDY1FQdql2Wvcy3RD91MHX5.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":461,"height":461}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91547"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-19T12:55:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-19T12:57:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6474"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109192"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"29","links":{"sel